lead_paragraph: ROBINSON--Carmen Maria Warren. On Wednesday, June 11, Carmen Maria Warren Robinson lost her courageous battle with cancer at age 63. Carmen was an accomplished equestrian, a talented painter, potter and floral artist; but it was her courage that truly inspired. Her family is grateful to Dr. Anna Gattani for helping her beat the odds as her cancer metastasized and to Dr. Sandra Park for keeping her grounded. Carmen's faith enabled her to live each day at its fullest with no worry about the next. The bible tells us of Enoch who walked with the Lord each day until one day they went much further than usual. The Lord said, "Enoch you have come so far with me, come just a little further and we will go home together." Carmen did just that; she walked a little further on the road all of us must travel. Carmen's dream was to train guide dogs for the blind. Donations may be sent in her memory to: guidedogs.com. A memorial service celebrating her life will be held on Saturday, August 16, at 2:00pm at the Trinity Methodist Church, City Island, NY. Carmen is survived by her husband, Ritch Robinson; her father, Peter Warren and stepmother Hollis; her sister AJ; her brother Peter, former wife Peggy and nephews, Josh, Peter and Aiden Warren; her Aunt Christina Bracho and cousins, Pablo, Juan and Diana and Giles and Hugh Parker. This obituary was submitted by the Warren and Robinson families. You may contact the family at: mariawarren2@yahoo.com.

lead_paragraph: MILMAN--Jeffrey Owen, born July 23, 1943, in New York City, died unexpectedly Friday, May 9, 2014, in Cleveland, Ohio. With fond memories of growing up in Scarsdale, NY, Jeff graduated from Cornell University, where he was treasurer and reunion director of the WVBR radio station, and Stanford University Graduate School of Business. Choosing to volunteer in Vietnam, Jeff was commissioned as a 2nd Lieutenant in the US Army Medical Service Corps, serving as a hospital administrator in Chu Lai, and later rose to Captain. A CPA, Jeff worked as comptroller for several companies, his favorite being the former Ideal Toy Company, for which he still planned gatherings with other employees. He was an avid skier, scuba diver, and boating enthusiast. A member of the New York Military Affairs Symposium, Jeff was dedicated to military history, making many friends with others similarly inclined. Jeff spent the past nine months in Cleveland, Ohio, to be closer to his nephew's family; Justin and Lisa were endlessly and selflessly devoted to him until his untimely death. Jeff made lifelong friends wherever paths crossed, he as devoted to them as they to him; his incredible kindness and generosity will not be forgotten. Beloved son of the late Morton and Rosalind Eno Milman, Jeff is survived by his brother Stephen Milman (Evalyn) of Darien, Connecticut, and his sister Kathryn Havemann of Dayton, Ohio. Close relatives included the families of Richard and Janet Eno of Cabot, Vermont, Robert and Candice Eno of Bloomington, Indiana, his nieces and nephews (Douglas, Natalie, Nadia, and Stephen Milman of Oakton, Virginia; Andrew, Shanna, and Matthew Milman of New York City; Justin, Lisa, Eamon, and Mallerie Havemann of Rocky River, Ohio; Margaret, Jared, Josephine, Charlotte, and Lucille Scogna of Arlington, Virginia; Elizabeth, Michael, Caden, Lucas, and Jack Casanova of Kettering, Ohio; Catherine Havemann of Columbus, Ohio). A service with Military Honors will be held in Cleveland Thursday, May 15, 2014 (details at http://buschfuneral.tributes.com/obituary/photos/Jeffrey-Owen-Milman-101347109), followed by prayers/ interment Sunday, May 18, 2014, at 11:00am, Mount Lebanon Cemetery, Glendale (Queens), New York. If desired, donations in Jeff's memory may be made to NAMI, P.O. Box 62596, Baltimore, MD 21264-2596, or online at www.nami.org. May his memory forever be a blessing.

lead_paragraph: CAMING--H. W. William. An advocate for international tribunals to investigate and prosecute crimes against humanity and a prominent figure in the history of telecommunications law and privacy, died January 24, 2014, at his home in Summit, NJ, at the age of 94. A Memorial Service for Mr. Caming will take place at the Calvary Episcopal Church, 31 Woodland Ave., Summit, NJ on Friday, April 11th at 10am. As chief prosecutor and deputy director of the Political Ministries Division in the Office of the United States Chief Counsel for War Crimes from 1946 to 1949, Caming charged 21 German military and civilian leaders with crimes against peace, war crimes, crimes against humanity, and membership in criminal organizations in the largest, longest, and last phase of the Nuremberg trials. In November 2011 he accepted the Joshua Heintz Award for Humanitarian Achievement from the Robert H. Jackson Center for his work. After his military service in World War II and at Nuremberg, Caming joined the New York State Attorney General's office and then in 1953 the Bell System. He moved to AT&T's headquarters in 1965 as senior counsel and until 1984 oversaw all legal matters related to privacy, corporate security, information technology, criminal law, and related litigation for AT&T and its affiliates, testifying frequently before Congressional committees and regulatory bodies. Before and after retiring in 1984, Caming served as a consultant on privacy matters to the CIA, FBI, Congress, and the American Bar Association Section on Criminal Justice. Caming graduated summa cum laude and Phi Beta Kappa from New York University in 1937. He also earned an L.L.M. in labor law from NYU and a J.D. from Harvard Law School. Born in New York City to a corporate and residential real estate developer and his wife, he was married for 54 years to Kathleen Marie (nee White) Caming, who died in 2005. He is survived by a daughter, Patricia Castillo of Elizabeth, NJ, and a brother, Lionel Caming of New York City and his dedicated caregiver, Ann McPherson. In lieu of flowers, those who wish may contribute in his memory to The H. W. William and Kathleen W. Caming Scholarship Fund at Drew University, c/o Drew University, 36 Madison Avenue, Madison, NJ, 07940. Services by Bradley, Brough & Dangler Funeral Home, Summit. For a complete obituary, additional information and to leave the family a message of condolence, please go to: bradleyfuneralhomes.com.

lead_paragraph: EVANS--Barton "Bart" Jr., passed away peacefully after a brave and always optimistic 19 month struggle with pancreatic cancer. Bart is survived by Harriet "Andrea" Neves, his loving wife and partner of nearly 35 years, his brother, Bruce Marshall Evans (Woodland Hills, California) and his sister, Barbara Ashwood Evans McDowell (Upper Saddle River, New Jersey). Bart was the son of Barton Evans, Sr. (1909-1979), born in Salem, Massachusetts, following a long line of Barton's dating back to John Barton, Sr. (1626-1690) of Huntingdon, England. A long succession of Barton's resided in Barton Square in Salem, Massachusetts. Bart was born on December 11, 1947 in Washington D.C. In 1952, the family moved to Pacific Palisades, California. He graduated from St. Matthew's School in 1960, and then completed his secondary education at Phillips Exeter Academy in 1966. Evans then entered the Management Engineering program at Claremont McKenna College (formerly Claremont Men's College). Completing the requirements for a Bachelor's degree in Economics, in 1969, he transferred to Stanford University where he graduated with Bachelors and Masters Degrees in Engineering in March, 1972. Upon graduation, Evans received his ROTC commission as a Second Lieutenant in the U.S. Army Signal Corps in March, 1972. He was assigned to the United States Army Strategic Communications Command-Europe in Mannheim, Germany where he served until release from active duty in January, 1975. In July, 1977, Evans joined Durrum Instrument Corporation (the parent of Dionex Corporation) as a senior engineer. He was advanced through a succession of engineering and executive positions until his retirement in 2003 from his position as the Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer of Dionex. During his 28-year career at Dionex, Evans developed the first dual-channel Ion Chromatograph. Evans holds a patent for "Conductivity Detector and Method" and has given several papers at the Pittsburg Conference in Analytical Chemistry and Applied Spectroscopy (PittCon), the most recent of which was an invitation to speak at the Twelfth Annual James L. Waters Annual Symposium, "recognizing pioneers in the development of analytical instrumentation." In parallel with his "civilian" career, Evans remained active in the U.S. Army Reserve. Following separation from active duty and return to the United States, Evans joined the 351st Civil Affairs Command in March, 1976, where he served in successive assignments. In March 1997, Colonel Evans became Chief, United States Army Pacific Support Team. His responsibilities were widened when he was assigned as Chief, Pacific Command Support Teams in January 1998, and later, and Chief of Staff in October 1998. In August, 2000 Colonel Evans became Deputy Commander, 351st Affairs Command, where he served until his retirement 30 April 2002 after over 30 plus years' military service. His awards and decorations include the Legion of Merit, Meritorious Service Medals, Army Commendation Medals, Army Achievement Medals, and Army Reserve Components Achievement Medals. In retirement, Evans was active in the volunteer arena. He was a trustee for Claremont McKenna College, serving on the Executive, Academic Affairs, Finance, Student Affairs Committees, and the Research Institutes sub-committee. He also chaired the President's Information Technology Advisory Board which was recently named the Evans ITAB. A supporter of the performing arts, Evans served as Secretary-Treasurer for the San Francisco Lyric Opera and was on the Board of Trustees for Opera San Jose. Evans was married to Dr. H. Andrea Neves, Professor of Education Emerita, Sonoma State University, and Lecturer, Stanford University School of Education. lead_paragraph: EVANS--Barton "Bart" Jr.,passed away peacefully after a brave and always optimistic 19 month struggle with pancreatic cancer. Bart is survived by Harriet "Andrea" Neves, his loving wife and partner of nearly 35 years, his brother, Bruce Marshall Evans (Woodland Hills, California) and his sister, Barbara Ashwood Evans McDowell (Upper Saddle River, New Jersey). Bart was the son of Barton Evans, Sr. (1909-1979), born in Salem, Massachusetts, following a long line of Barton's dating back to John Barton, Sr. (1626-1690) of Huntingdon, England. A long succession of Barton's resided in Barton Square in Salem, Massachusetts. Bart was born on December 11, 1947 in Washington D.C. In 1952, the family moved to Pacific Palisades, California. He graduated from St. Matthew's School in 1960, and then completed his secondary education at Phillips Exeter Academy in 1966. Evans then entered the Management Engineering program at Claremont McKenna College (formerly Claremont Men's College). Completing the requirements for a Bachelor's degree in Economics, in 1969, he transferred to Stanford University where he graduated with Bachelors and Masters Degrees in Engineering in March, 1972. Upon graduation, Evans received his ROTC commission as a Second Lieutenant in the U.S. Army Signal Corps in March, 1972. He was assigned to the United States Army Strategic Communications Command-Europe in Mannheim, Germany where he served until release from active duty in January, 1975. In July, 1977, Evans joined Durrum Instrument Corporation (the parent of Dionex Corporation) as a senior engineer. He was advanced through a succession of engineering and executive positions until his retirement in 2003 from his position as the Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer of Dionex. During his 28-year career at Dionex, Evans developed the first dual-channel Ion Chromatograph. Evans holds a patent for "Conductivity Detector and Method" and has given several papers at the Pittsburg Conference in Analytical Chemistry and Applied Spectroscopy (PittCon), the most recent of which was an invitation to speak at the Twelfth Annual James L. Waters Annual Symposium, "recognizing pioneers in the development of analytical instrumentation." In parallel with his "civilian" career, Evans remained active in the U.S. Army Reserve. Following separation from active duty and return to the United States, Evans joined the 351st Civil Affairs Command in March, 1976, where he served in successive assignments. In March 1997, Colonel Evans became Chief, United States Army Pacific Support Team. His responsibilities were widened when he was assigned as Chief, Pacific Command Support Teams in January 1998, and later, and Chief of Staff in October 1998. In August, 2000 Colonel Evans became Deputy Commander, 351st Affairs Command, where he served until his retirement 30 April 2002 after over 30 plus years' military service. His awards and decorations include the Legion of Merit, Meritorious Service Medals, Army Commendation Medals, Army Achievement Medals, and Army Reserve Components Achievement Medals. In retirement, Evans was active in the volunteer arena. He was a trustee for Claremont McKenna College, serving on the Executive, Academic Affairs, Finance, Student Affairs Committees, and the Research Institutes sub-committee. He also chaired the President's Information Technology Advisory Board which was recently named the Evans ITAB. A supporter of the performing arts, Evans served as Secretary-Treasurer for the San Francisco Lyric Opera and was on the Board of Trustees for Opera San Jose. Evans was married to Dr. H.
